{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505917"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:38:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:38:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2498"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2498"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.67,0.04,0.19,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2498"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105985"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2498"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2498"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88460"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"1546"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"7982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2280"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3082"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43169"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105985"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year old woman presents with a burning red rash on her lower legs that has been present for one week. It is worse at the end of the day after she has been at work. She feels otherwise well, though on further history, stated that several weeks ago she had a sore throat and headache for which she took ibuprofen. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she appears well. Her pulse rate is 68/min and blood pressure 135/88mmHg. There are palpable petechiae and purpura across bilateral dorsum of feet, ankles and distal shins. Below her right lateral malleolus there is an ulcer in the centre of coalesced purpuric lesions. The rash is non-blanching. There are no other skin findings elsewhere. A skin biopsy was taken, showing a perivascular neutrophilic infiltrate with leukocytoclasis and fibrinoid necrosis of the vessels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common cause of this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Exercise","Viral infection","External trauma","Diabetes","Chronic kidney disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecutaneous small vessel vasculitis (CSVV).\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are many possible causes of CSVV: reaction to medications, reaction to food or food additives, underlying infection, autoimmune connective tissue disease, or malignancy. In approximately one third to half of cases CSVV is idiopathic. Out of the options above, \u003Cstrong\u003Eviral infection\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common. \u003Cstrong\u003EExercise-induced vasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E can occur but is less commonly the primary cause and generally presents with milder clinical features. Cutaneous or systemic vasculitis can also be aggravated by exercise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the case described above, the cause could be a viral infection, or a reaction to ibuprofen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal trauma\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetes\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E are not causes of CSVV. In a patient with CSVV, it is important to perform blood and urine tests to exclude systemic vasculitis involving the kidneys.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Underlying causes of cutaneous small vessel vasculitis include reaction to medications, reaction to food or food additives, underlying infection, autoimmune connective tissue disease, or malignancy.","In one third to a half of individuals affected by cutaneous small vessel vasculitis the cause is idiopathic."],"references":["Goeser MR, Laniosz V, Wetter DA. A practical approach to the diagnosis, evaluation, and management of cutaneous small-vessel vasculitis. Am J Clin Dermatol. 2014;15(4):299-306. Available from: https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s40257-014-0076-6","Micheletti RG. Cutaneous Small Vessel Vasculitis: A Practical Guide to Diagnosis and Management. Am J Clin Dermatol. 2023 Jan;24(1):89-95. doi: 10.1007/s40257-022-00736-6. Epub 2022 Oct 29. PMID: 36308673. Avaialble from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36308673/","Russell JP, Weenig RH. Primary Cutaneous Small Vessel Vasculitis. Curr Treat Options Cardiovasc Med. 2004 Apr;6(2):139-149. doi: 10.1007/s11936-004-0042-3. PMID: 15066243. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15066243/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88460"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2498"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88460"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-15T17:36:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-18T21:13:17+09:30"},"relationsh